WEBVTT

1
00:00:02.500 --> 00:00:03.680
Good afternoon, everyone.

2
00:00:06.040 --> 00:00:08.120
Welcome to our mini symposium,

3
00:00:09.440 --> 00:00:13.340
"Population Sciences at the Forefront: Risk Factors Influencing

4
00:00:13.500 --> 00:00:15.500
Cancer Incidence and Survival."

5
00:00:16.460 --> 00:00:19.200
It's my pleasure to co-chair this session with

6
00:00:20.480 --> 00:00:22.300
Dr. Melissa Troster.

7
00:00:23.460 --> 00:00:27.020
Population sciences, as you know, are very essential

8
00:00:27.900 --> 00:00:29.820
to advancing cancer research,

9
00:00:30.640 --> 00:00:34.520
not only on identifying who is at risk, but in

10
00:00:34.580 --> 00:00:38.340
understanding the complex interplay of lifestyle,

11
00:00:38.620 --> 00:00:42.320
clinical, environmental, genetic, structural factors that shape

12
00:00:42.380 --> 00:00:44.220
cancer incidence and survival.

13
00:00:45.760 --> 00:00:46.900
So today's session

14
00:00:48.000 --> 00:00:51.710
will bring together an outstanding set of studies spanning the

15
00:00:51.760 --> 00:00:55.080
continuum from early life exposures to

16
00:00:55.120 --> 00:00:59.020
survivorship, and from population-level risk factors to

17
00:00:59.120 --> 00:01:00.520
genomic discovery.

18
00:01:01.380 --> 00:01:05.060
We will begin with Phuong Anh Le, who examines

19
00:01:05.620 --> 00:01:08.660
adherence to planetary health diet during

20
00:01:08.760 --> 00:01:12.660
adolescence and its association with

21
00:01:12.780 --> 00:01:16.580
breast cancer risks, highlighting the importance of early life

22
00:01:16.640 --> 00:01:17.420
exposures.

23
00:01:18.380 --> 00:01:21.620
And then next, Kevin Chen will present on

24
00:01:21.780 --> 00:01:25.580
cardiorespiratory multimorbidity and lung cancer risks,

25
00:01:26.340 --> 00:01:29.960
offering insights into how coexisting

26
00:01:30.060 --> 00:01:33.620
chronic conditions may influence cancer development.

27
00:01:35.160 --> 00:01:38.560
Catherine De La Torre Cineiros will then examine

28
00:01:38.620 --> 00:01:42.510
generation immigration status and

29
00:01:42.580 --> 00:01:45.850
gastric cancer incidence among Japanese

30
00:01:45.920 --> 00:01:49.820
descendants in the multiethnic cohort, which underscore the

31
00:01:49.880 --> 00:01:52.240
importance of population heterogeneity.

32
00:01:53.680 --> 00:01:57.540
We then move into translational research with Loukas

33
00:01:58.000 --> 00:02:01.900
Mavromatis, who will discuss an EHR-based model for

34
00:02:02.020 --> 00:02:04.020
pancreatic cancer risk stratification.

35
00:02:05.320 --> 00:02:09.060
Following this, Shital Hardikar will explore metabolic

36
00:02:09.160 --> 00:02:12.800
factors and survival outcomes after colorectal cancer.

37
00:02:14.120 --> 00:02:17.400
We will then hear from Sakshat Chintala, who examines

38
00:02:17.480 --> 00:02:21.380
disparities in telehealth utilization in cancer

39
00:02:21.520 --> 00:02:24.860
care, highlighting important issues in health equity.

40
00:02:25.860 --> 00:02:29.440
And finally, we will conclude with a presentation from the

41
00:02:29.520 --> 00:02:32.840
NCI Confluence Project, the largest

42
00:02:32.920 --> 00:02:36.200
multi-ancestry GWAS study of breast cancer to date.

43
00:02:37.240 --> 00:02:40.480
So across these talks, key themes include

44
00:02:41.180 --> 00:02:44.100
life course exposures, multimorbidity,

45
00:02:44.760 --> 00:02:46.180
population diversity,

46
00:02:47.060 --> 00:02:51.030
and the integration of epidemiology with clinical data and genomics.

47
00:02:51.700 --> 00:02:55.020
So with that, I'm delighted to introduce our first speaker,

48
00:02:55.820 --> 00:02:56.360
Phuong Anh Le.

49
00:03:00.700 --> 00:03:03.140
I

50
00:03:03.150 --> 00:03:12.880
think

51
00:03:13.440 --> 00:03:13.630
you

52
00:03:13.630 --> 00:03:24.720
have

53
00:03:24.790 --> 00:03:25.030
to hit the

54
00:03:25.030 --> 00:03:31.120
computer.

55
00:03:31.180 --> 00:03:32.920
Sorry.

56
00:03:33.120 --> 00:03:35.350
Try just hitting it. Just check.

57
00:03:35.420 --> 00:03:35.620
Okay.

58
00:03:37.400 --> 00:03:39.240
Hello, everyone. My name is Phuong Anh.

59
00:03:39.280 --> 00:03:42.320
I'm a PhD student at the Harvard Chan School of Public Health,

60
00:03:43.140 --> 00:03:45.260
and I'm honored to be here today to share with you

61
00:03:46.460 --> 00:03:50.220
our current research looking at the adherence to the EAT-Lancet reference

62
00:03:50.280 --> 00:03:53.940
diet in adolescence and the risk of invasive breast cancer

63
00:03:54.280 --> 00:03:56.000
in adulthood among US women.

64
00:03:59.140 --> 00:04:02.440
And so why are we interested in adolescent diet?

65
00:04:03.360 --> 00:04:07.040
Adolescence is a special period that is marked by significant

66
00:04:07.120 --> 00:04:10.600
hormone changes and rapid proliferation of the breast tissues,

67
00:04:11.020 --> 00:04:14.240
making it a susceptible window for breast carcinogenesis.

68
00:04:15.340 --> 00:04:18.981
However, despite the importance of this period, most current

69
00:04:19.041 --> 00:04:22.990
studies focus on the adult diet and breast cancer, and mainly it's

70
00:04:23.000 --> 00:04:26.880
because there aren't a lot of studies that have data on

71
00:04:26.900 --> 00:04:27.920
adolescent diet.

72
00:04:29.680 --> 00:04:32.980
According to a recent systematic review and meta-analysis,

73
00:04:33.400 --> 00:04:36.600
several adolescent dietary factors were found to

74
00:04:36.960 --> 00:04:40.140
significantly reduce the risk of adult breast cancer,

75
00:04:40.940 --> 00:04:44.520
including fruit and vegetables, soy, dietary

76
00:04:44.580 --> 00:04:46.160
fiber, and vegetable fat.

77
00:04:48.180 --> 00:04:52.050
Just a little background on the dietary pattern that we are looking at today,

78
00:04:52.180 --> 00:04:55.040
which is called the Planetary Health Dietary Index.

79
00:04:55.940 --> 00:04:59.700
So in 2019, the EAT-Lancet Commission proposed

80
00:05:00.020 --> 00:05:03.740
a dietary pattern that is simultaneously beneficial for human

81
00:05:03.820 --> 00:05:07.580
health as well as for the sustainability of the planet.

82
00:05:08.670 --> 00:05:12.280
And then subsequently, this dietary pattern, called the

83
00:05:12.300 --> 00:05:16.220
Planetary Health Dietary Index, was developed to quantify adherence

84
00:05:16.260 --> 00:05:18.780
to this EAT-Lancet reference diet.

85
00:05:19.720 --> 00:05:23.640
And from previous research, we know that adherence to this diet

86
00:05:23.680 --> 00:05:27.530
was linked to a lower risk of cardiovascular disease, type 2 diabetes,

87
00:05:27.720 --> 00:05:29.380
as well as all-cause mortality.

88
00:05:30.980 --> 00:05:34.260
And in our group, we found that a higher adult

89
00:05:34.420 --> 00:05:37.910
adherence to this Planetary Health Dietary Index was

90
00:05:37.980 --> 00:05:41.600
associated with a lower breast cancer risk, and we saw a

91
00:05:41.680 --> 00:05:44.460
stronger association for ER-negative tumors.

92
00:05:45.870 --> 00:05:49.610
And with all of this, that's why we are interested in looking at adolescent

93
00:05:49.920 --> 00:05:53.880
Planetary Health Dietary Index. So this is a score that

94
00:05:54.420 --> 00:05:58.220
contains a sum of 14 food groups characterized by high

95
00:05:58.260 --> 00:06:00.840
intake of whole grain, vegetables, fruits-

96
00:06:01.268 --> 00:06:05.048
nuts, legumes, unsaturated oils, with low to

97
00:06:05.068 --> 00:06:08.828
moderate intake of dairy, poultry, egg, and fish, and

98
00:06:08.908 --> 00:06:12.688
low to limited intake of starchy vegetables, red processed meat,

99
00:06:13.028 --> 00:06:16.648
added saturated fat, and added sugar and sugar from juice.

100
00:06:19.088 --> 00:06:22.768
And so to just reiterate our study objectives, we

101
00:06:22.808 --> 00:06:26.578
wanted to assess the association between adolescent Planetary

102
00:06:26.628 --> 00:06:29.788
Health Dietary Index and subsequent risk of breast cancer.

103
00:06:30.768 --> 00:06:34.288
And we will also examine if the association differ by estrogen

104
00:06:34.408 --> 00:06:34.848
status,

105
00:06:35.728 --> 00:06:37.508
receptor status of the tumors,

106
00:06:38.448 --> 00:06:42.288
by menopausal status at diagnosis, as well as by body mass

107
00:06:42.348 --> 00:06:43.908
index at age 18.

108
00:06:46.688 --> 00:06:50.488
So we used the Nurses' Health Study Too, which is a well-known cohort

109
00:06:50.948 --> 00:06:54.517
of more than 100,000 nurses. And these

110
00:06:54.528 --> 00:06:58.188
participants filled out questionnaires every two years to report their

111
00:06:58.248 --> 00:07:01.948
outcome, including breast cancer, as well as other

112
00:07:02.008 --> 00:07:05.307
covariates like lifestyle factors and reproductive factors.

113
00:07:06.447 --> 00:07:09.228
And within this cohort, there were more than

114
00:07:09.868 --> 00:07:11.748
47,000 women,

115
00:07:12.568 --> 00:07:16.118
age 33 and 52 years old at baseline, filled out

116
00:07:16.528 --> 00:07:20.138
a validated 124-item food frequency questionnaire in

117
00:07:20.148 --> 00:07:23.208
1998 to recall their adolescent diet.

118
00:07:24.268 --> 00:07:27.748
And then we followed them prospectively from 1998 until

119
00:07:29.248 --> 00:07:32.588
2019, which is about 20 years of follow-up.

120
00:07:33.888 --> 00:07:37.728
And as you can see in this diagram, the key point is that in

121
00:07:37.768 --> 00:07:41.698
1998, these participants recalled their adolescent diet years

122
00:07:41.728 --> 00:07:45.418
ago, so 15 to 35 years ago. But the study design is

123
00:07:45.428 --> 00:07:48.648
prospective, because we followed them prospectively from

124
00:07:48.668 --> 00:07:49.688
1998

125
00:07:50.648 --> 00:07:52.008
for incident breast cancer.

126
00:07:54.528 --> 00:07:58.448
And our exposure is the quartiles of the adolescent PHDI, and we

127
00:07:58.588 --> 00:08:02.268
used cause proportional hazard models to look at these associations.

128
00:08:03.148 --> 00:08:07.098
And in our models, we adjusted for potential

129
00:08:07.128 --> 00:08:10.378
confounders of this association, as well as

130
00:08:10.648 --> 00:08:14.508
well-known risk factors for breast cancer, including adolescent

131
00:08:14.568 --> 00:08:18.248
characteristics as well as adult reproductive and lifestyle factors.

132
00:08:19.428 --> 00:08:23.148
And in a separate model, we also adjusted for weight change to

133
00:08:23.248 --> 00:08:27.008
see if the association was attenuated after we account for weight

134
00:08:27.088 --> 00:08:27.468
change.

135
00:08:29.788 --> 00:08:33.408
So just briefly to look at the baseline characteristics of the participants.

136
00:08:34.208 --> 00:08:38.108
So across quartiles of the PHDI, those who were

137
00:08:38.148 --> 00:08:41.668
at higher quartiles had lower adolescent total energy

138
00:08:41.788 --> 00:08:42.188
intake,

139
00:08:43.468 --> 00:08:46.388
as well as less likely to have ever drunk alcohol

140
00:08:46.448 --> 00:08:50.088
and as well as less likely to have ever

141
00:08:50.388 --> 00:08:54.328
used oral contraceptive. But interestingly, those who were at higher

142
00:08:54.348 --> 00:08:57.988
quartiles were more likely to have early age at

143
00:08:58.028 --> 00:08:58.528
menarche.

144
00:09:00.348 --> 00:09:04.288
Looking at the adult factors, we also saw that those who were

145
00:09:04.328 --> 00:09:07.168
at the higher quartiles has less weight change

146
00:09:08.068 --> 00:09:11.368
since age 18, more adult physical activity,

147
00:09:11.808 --> 00:09:12.238
and

148
00:09:13.088 --> 00:09:15.068
less likely to have ever had children.

149
00:09:19.608 --> 00:09:20.528
They were also

150
00:09:21.488 --> 00:09:23.868
more likely to have ever breastfed.

151
00:09:23.968 --> 00:09:27.468
And among post-menopausal women, those with higher

152
00:09:27.488 --> 00:09:30.908
quartiles were also less likely to have ever used

153
00:09:31.468 --> 00:09:32.628
post-menopausal hormone.

154
00:09:35.268 --> 00:09:38.568
And this is the main results of our study.

155
00:09:38.648 --> 00:09:42.408
So looking at adolescent PHDI and breast cancer,

156
00:09:42.528 --> 00:09:46.228
we did not see an association for overall invasive breast

157
00:09:46.268 --> 00:09:49.337
cancer as well as for ER-positive breast cancer.

158
00:09:49.908 --> 00:09:53.548
However, we did see that adhering to this EAT-Lancet reference

159
00:09:53.588 --> 00:09:57.508
diet during adolescence significantly reduced future risks of

160
00:09:57.548 --> 00:09:59.668
breast cancer by more than 30%.

161
00:10:00.528 --> 00:10:04.308
And what is noteworthy is that after we adjust for potential

162
00:10:04.368 --> 00:10:08.048
confounders, the associations did not change a lot

163
00:10:08.408 --> 00:10:09.348
throughout our models.

164
00:10:10.288 --> 00:10:14.108
And the association remained significant even after adjusting for weight change

165
00:10:14.528 --> 00:10:15.368
since age 18.

166
00:10:17.768 --> 00:10:21.608
And then we looked further to see if this association differs by menopausal

167
00:10:21.668 --> 00:10:25.148
status as well as by subgroups of BMI at age 18.

168
00:10:26.308 --> 00:10:30.028
And for overall invasive breast cancer, we did not see any

169
00:10:30.428 --> 00:10:34.308
effect modification by menopausal status as well as by

170
00:10:34.348 --> 00:10:38.028
BMI at age 18. And similarly, for ER-positive breast

171
00:10:38.088 --> 00:10:41.568
cancer, we did not see any differences in the association

172
00:10:41.928 --> 00:10:45.688
across subgroups of menopausal status as well as subgroups of BMI at

173
00:10:45.748 --> 00:10:46.308
age 18.

174
00:10:48.288 --> 00:10:51.148
But for ER-negative breast cancer, we saw something different.

175
00:10:51.688 --> 00:10:55.328
So we saw that among premenopausal ER-negative breast

176
00:10:55.388 --> 00:10:59.268
cancer, there was a significant reductions in breast cancer risk.

177
00:10:59.608 --> 00:11:03.508
However, it was not significant among post-menopausal

178
00:11:03.568 --> 00:11:04.808
ER-negative breast cancer.

179
00:11:06.528 --> 00:11:10.068
And when looking at BMI at age 18 subgroups, we also saw a

180
00:11:10.128 --> 00:11:14.108
significant association among those who were below 21

181
00:11:14.148 --> 00:11:15.468
kilogram per meter square

182
00:11:16.268 --> 00:11:20.008
at age 18, but did not see a significant association for the other

183
00:11:20.068 --> 00:11:20.388
group.

184
00:11:21.428 --> 00:11:25.328
However, looking at these results, it's important to keep in mind

185
00:11:25.338 --> 00:11:29.158
that our sample size was somewhat limited when looking at

186
00:11:29.248 --> 00:11:33.068
these subgroups. For instance, we only had 83 cases

187
00:11:33.128 --> 00:11:35.787
of premenopausal ER-negative breast cancer.

188
00:11:37.908 --> 00:11:41.248
And then we just go a little bit further and try to see

189
00:11:41.668 --> 00:11:45.128
which food groups have driven the

190
00:11:45.188 --> 00:11:48.028
association we have seen in ER-negative breast cancer.

191
00:11:49.208 --> 00:11:52.828
So we saw that whole fruits was protective for breast cancer.

192
00:11:53.988 --> 00:11:57.668
However, saturated fat and added saturated fat and trans fat

193
00:11:58.108 --> 00:11:59.888
increased the risk of future breast

194
00:11:59.928 --> 00:12:03.904
cancer.And for premenopausal

195
00:12:03.944 --> 00:12:07.764
ER-negative breast cancer, we also see that whole fruits were protective,

196
00:12:08.684 --> 00:12:12.404
and added saturated fat and trans fat increased the risk.

197
00:12:12.924 --> 00:12:16.864
And we additionally saw that starchy vegetables

198
00:12:16.944 --> 00:12:20.484
slightly increased the risk for premenopausal

199
00:12:20.524 --> 00:12:24.504
ER-negative breast cancer. But again, we only had 83 cases for

200
00:12:24.544 --> 00:12:25.404
this subgroup.

201
00:12:26.924 --> 00:12:30.874
So what do we interpret and kind of key message

202
00:12:30.874 --> 00:12:31.674
out of all of this?

203
00:12:32.584 --> 00:12:36.104
So we found that greater adherence to the EAT-Lancet diet in

204
00:12:36.124 --> 00:12:40.044
adolescent was associated with a lower risk of ER-negative

205
00:12:40.084 --> 00:12:43.244
breast cancer, particularly among premenopausal women,

206
00:12:44.064 --> 00:12:48.024
and among those with BMI less than 21 kilogram per meter square

207
00:12:48.064 --> 00:12:51.104
at age 18. And this EAT-Lancet

208
00:12:51.384 --> 00:12:55.284
diet again was developed so that it was beneficial for both

209
00:12:55.344 --> 00:12:57.684
humans and sustainable for the planet.

210
00:12:59.124 --> 00:13:02.674
And the apparent specificity that we saw for ER-negative tumors is

211
00:13:02.704 --> 00:13:06.314
notable because we do not know a lot of modifiable risk

212
00:13:06.404 --> 00:13:10.364
factors for this subtype, although this is the more aggressive subtype

213
00:13:10.404 --> 00:13:11.244
of breast cancer.

214
00:13:13.084 --> 00:13:16.484
And given the fact that there are limitations to our studies, especially the

215
00:13:16.524 --> 00:13:20.244
recalled aspect of the diet, additional prospective

216
00:13:20.304 --> 00:13:23.804
cohort studies are needed, especially to look at more

217
00:13:23.864 --> 00:13:27.844
intermediate outcomes like mammographic density or benign breast

218
00:13:27.904 --> 00:13:28.344
disease,

219
00:13:29.704 --> 00:13:32.384
would be needed to confirm this hypothesis.

220
00:13:33.364 --> 00:13:36.934
And if confirmed, a plant-forward adolescent diet may have dual

221
00:13:36.964 --> 00:13:40.804
benefits for breast cancer prevention as well as for planetary health.

222
00:13:42.664 --> 00:13:45.004
And lastly, I would like to thank my co-authors,

223
00:13:46.124 --> 00:13:49.644
funders, as well as special thanks to the Nurses' Health Study 2 participants

224
00:13:50.164 --> 00:13:53.644
for their longstanding dedication and invaluable contribution to this

225
00:13:53.684 --> 00:13:54.164
research.

226
00:13:54.984 --> 00:13:55.984
Thank you for listening.

227
00:14:17.184 --> 00:14:20.624
Thank you for the great talk. I was wondering if you have any further

228
00:14:20.784 --> 00:14:24.244
plan to look for most susceptible window period

229
00:14:24.464 --> 00:14:28.084
for exposure to this diet by

230
00:14:28.124 --> 00:14:31.944
comparing, I mean, applying the same method to the different

231
00:14:31.984 --> 00:14:35.624
age groups, including adolescents and different age groups into adults,

232
00:14:36.184 --> 00:14:39.984
so that we can find if the adolescent period is more

233
00:14:40.004 --> 00:14:43.204
susceptible than other age group in terms of

234
00:14:43.244 --> 00:14:45.024
exposure period.

235
00:14:45.084 --> 00:14:46.124
Yeah. So,

236
00:14:47.444 --> 00:14:51.184
a previous study in our group looked at this pattern in the

237
00:14:51.244 --> 00:14:53.684
adult diet and saw similar

238
00:14:54.964 --> 00:14:58.344
results with this study. So we also found that

239
00:14:59.124 --> 00:15:02.984
adherence to this diet during adult reduced the risk of overall breast cancer as

240
00:15:03.004 --> 00:15:06.584
well as in stronger associations for ER-negative breast cancer.

241
00:15:07.184 --> 00:15:10.774
And so one of the next step that we are thinking about is to look

242
00:15:10.804 --> 00:15:14.754
at whether people who are consistently adhering to

243
00:15:14.784 --> 00:15:18.504
this diet, both in adolescent and adult, would reduce

244
00:15:19.064 --> 00:15:20.724
the risk of cancer. Yeah.

245
00:15:20.884 --> 00:15:23.464
Have you looked into the effect size?

246
00:15:25.224 --> 00:15:25.644
I'm sorry?

247
00:15:26.504 --> 00:15:29.924
Have you compared the effect size in adolescents and

248
00:15:29.984 --> 00:15:30.524
adulthood?

249
00:15:31.904 --> 00:15:35.744
I don't have the number for the adults on top of my mind,

250
00:15:35.844 --> 00:15:37.364
but what was similar was

251
00:15:38.264 --> 00:15:41.934
that both of the studies found stronger

252
00:15:41.964 --> 00:15:43.834
association for ER-negative breast cancer.

253
00:15:43.924 --> 00:15:44.393
Okay. Thank you.

254
00:15:44.393 --> 00:15:44.624
Thank you.

255
00:15:47.844 --> 00:15:49.644
Hi. I just have a quick question.

256
00:15:50.844 --> 00:15:53.924
I was wondering if you can explain the rationale for the BMI to be

257
00:15:54.084 --> 00:15:55.344
21.1?

258
00:15:56.124 --> 00:15:56.644
Yeah. So,

259
00:15:57.584 --> 00:16:01.324
this is just something particular to this particular study because,

