with higher incidence of PDAC using an EHR-based risk model.

803
00:47:59.778 --> 00:48:03.218
After that, these higher risk individuals would be screened with a blood-based

804
00:48:03.258 --> 00:48:07.058
biomarker test that would have appropriate and sufficient performance

805
00:48:07.118 --> 00:48:09.758
characteristics in a higher risk population to be clinically useful.

806
00:48:10.518 --> 00:48:14.238
And then finally, individuals who are positive for both the first steps of this

807
00:48:14.298 --> 00:48:15.358
sequence would

808
00:48:16.478 --> 00:48:18.998
undergo diagnostic imaging, such as MRI.

809
00:48:19.498 --> 00:48:23.038
This effectively reserves the most costly and

810
00:48:23.098 --> 00:48:26.058
effective screening method, which is imaging, for the highest risk

811
00:48:26.158 --> 00:48:30.136
patients.So in this study, we try to address this first

812
00:48:30.206 --> 00:48:33.906
step of this paradigm, this define step, by attempting to

813
00:48:33.926 --> 00:48:37.766
develop a validated and interpretable EHR model to define a high-risk

814
00:48:37.806 --> 00:48:38.966
population for PDAC.

815
00:48:40.966 --> 00:48:44.306
So other models have been developed to identify high-risk PDAC

816
00:48:44.326 --> 00:48:46.986
populations. Here are some of the notable ones.

817
00:48:47.486 --> 00:48:51.166
So NPAC is a well-validated, the only prospectively

818
00:48:51.206 --> 00:48:54.406
validated, and it's a deployable model

819
00:48:54.966 --> 00:48:58.786
that basically risk stratifies individuals ages 50 plus who have

820
00:48:58.806 --> 00:49:02.526
new onset diabetes. It includes variables including

821
00:49:02.566 --> 00:49:06.436
glucose trajectory, weight trajectory, age of diagnosis of

822
00:49:06.466 --> 00:49:10.306
T2D. But of course, it's only applicable to individuals

823
00:49:10.346 --> 00:49:13.736
who have new onset diabetes, and this is a minority of PDAC cases.

824
00:49:14.366 --> 00:49:17.746
Cancer RiskNet is another notable example of one of these EHR models.

825
00:49:18.106 --> 00:49:22.006
This is a transformer-based model that uses ICD codes

826
00:49:22.046 --> 00:49:24.886
as inputs and was developed in a large Danish registry.

827
00:49:25.506 --> 00:49:29.366
It performed very well there. It was attempted to validate in

828
00:49:29.406 --> 00:49:31.646
the US, in the VA population,

829
00:49:32.526 --> 00:49:35.666
and discrimination dropped from 0.88 to 0.71.

830
00:49:36.686 --> 00:49:40.066
This kind of underscores the challenge and the importance of

831
00:49:40.766 --> 00:49:44.646
developing these models in diverse clinical populations that

832
00:49:44.666 --> 00:49:47.436
sort of reflect the heterogeneity of the US clinical population.

833
00:49:48.366 --> 00:49:52.026
Additionally, this model included some non-specific codes like observation for

834
00:49:52.066 --> 00:49:55.416
suspected disease and uncertain neoplasm that were potentially suggestive of

835
00:49:55.906 --> 00:49:57.576
PDAC workup that was already ongoing.

836
00:49:58.476 --> 00:50:01.906
So our goal was to build on these models and use variables that precede clinical

837
00:50:01.986 --> 00:50:05.726
suspicion rather than markers of ongoing workup to develop, again, an

838
00:50:05.786 --> 00:50:09.546
interpretable and deployable risk stratification model for PDAC that

839
00:50:09.566 --> 00:50:12.646
would generalize across US health systems.

840
00:50:13.926 --> 00:50:16.286
To do this, we used the OptumLabs Data Warehouse.

841
00:50:16.326 --> 00:50:18.846
This is a large EHR and claims data set.

842
00:50:19.326 --> 00:50:22.966
Includes over 300 million individuals from health systems across the US with

843
00:50:23.006 --> 00:50:26.666
various insurance types and longitudinal data on those individuals.

844
00:50:27.406 --> 00:50:31.156
We took individuals who had a BMI measurement between 2016 and

845
00:50:31.346 --> 00:50:32.066
2018,

846
00:50:33.546 --> 00:50:37.346
were ages 40 plus, and had at least one prior year of observation in

847
00:50:37.415 --> 00:50:40.665
the EHR data set, and we enrolled them in this

848
00:50:41.066 --> 00:50:44.966
cohort. We divided our health systems, which were 54

849
00:50:45.046 --> 00:50:48.486
total US health systems, into training health systems and validation health

850
00:50:48.566 --> 00:50:49.006
systems.

851
00:50:49.966 --> 00:50:53.626
So we had 4.9 million individuals in the training health

852
00:50:53.666 --> 00:50:57.246
systems, which were 23 of the 54, and then 31 were the validation health

853
00:50:57.326 --> 00:50:57.746
systems.

854
00:50:59.386 --> 00:51:02.546
You can see the baseline characteristics, select baseline

855
00:51:02.586 --> 00:51:05.746
characteristics of our validation cohort.

856
00:51:05.866 --> 00:51:09.626
So the mean age was around 60, 79% of individuals were White,

857
00:51:10.206 --> 00:51:14.166
57% female, 40% ever smoker with a mean BMI of 30

858
00:51:14.226 --> 00:51:16.366
and a mean A1C of 6.4%.

859
00:51:17.206 --> 00:51:20.886
Our incidence rate of PDAC in this population was higher than the US population

860
00:51:21.126 --> 00:51:24.886
incidence rate due to the healthcare-seeking nature of the patients and the

861
00:51:24.926 --> 00:51:27.026
exclusion of younger individuals younger than 40.

862
00:51:28.586 --> 00:51:32.426
To develop our risk model in this population, we selected

863
00:51:32.506 --> 00:51:36.236
a group of hypothesis-driven candidate variables, largely from this

864
00:51:36.246 --> 00:51:40.186
phenome-wide association study conducted at NYU, in addition to a literature

865
00:51:40.226 --> 00:51:43.446
review to identify other known or plausible risk factors for PDAC.

866
00:51:44.146 --> 00:51:47.786
We then used an elastic net regression with cross-validation and

867
00:51:48.006 --> 00:51:51.966
missing indicators for missing continuous variables to basically

868
00:51:52.026 --> 00:51:55.946
parse down our candidate variables into independent and important

869
00:51:55.966 --> 00:51:59.746
risk factors. We ultimately selected 19 final

870
00:51:59.786 --> 00:52:03.766
variables, which were used to develop an unpenalized Cox

871
00:52:03.806 --> 00:52:07.506
model in the training cohort with the selected variables, and our

872
00:52:07.576 --> 00:52:10.726
outcome was incident PDAC as defined by ICD code.

873
00:52:12.766 --> 00:52:16.086
So here are the 19 variables that were selected in our training

874
00:52:16.766 --> 00:52:20.355
health systems, and you can see they include a number of sort of

875
00:52:20.406 --> 00:52:23.986
common risk factors that we all know of for pancreatic cancer.

876
00:52:24.046 --> 00:52:27.446
History of pancreatitis, history of other cancers,

877
00:52:27.626 --> 00:52:30.446
demographics including older age, male sex,

878
00:52:31.286 --> 00:52:34.966
Black race, metabolic and clinical variables including type 2

879
00:52:35.006 --> 00:52:38.866
diabetes, abnormal weight loss, as well as various GI

880
00:52:38.926 --> 00:52:42.886
conditions, and then laboratory values like A1C, glucose, lipase,

881
00:52:42.926 --> 00:52:46.706
and AST, as well as type O blood and smoking

882
00:52:46.766 --> 00:52:47.186
status.

883
00:52:50.606 --> 00:52:54.326
This figure here displays the performance of our model in our 31

884
00:52:54.366 --> 00:52:58.306
validation health systems. So you can see that the time-dependent area under

885
00:52:58.366 --> 00:53:01.526
the curve at 24 months is 0.76 and then

886
00:53:01.566 --> 00:53:03.366
0.75 at 36 months.

887
00:53:04.306 --> 00:53:07.206
Additionally, the calibration of our model was good,

888
00:53:08.166 --> 00:53:12.146
meaning the observed and predicted risk lined up well with a calibration slope of

889
00:53:12.326 --> 00:53:13.126
1.02.

890
00:53:17.286 --> 00:53:20.946
This displays hypothetical 36-month screening yield in the US validation

891
00:53:20.986 --> 00:53:24.826
cohort. So if you were to take the top 1% of highest predicted risk individuals

892
00:53:24.866 --> 00:53:28.656
per prime, these are individuals that have at least a 0.61%

893
00:53:28.746 --> 00:53:32.386
absolute three-year risk of PDAC in our model.

894
00:53:32.446 --> 00:53:36.366
Among these individuals, one of every 128 would actually develop PDAC within three

895
00:53:36.386 --> 00:53:40.186
years, and this would comprise 5.8% of all PDAC cases that occurred

896
00:53:40.226 --> 00:53:43.766
within three years. And you can see similar numbers as you drop the prime

897
00:53:43.786 --> 00:53:47.126
percentile to the top 10%. You have a lower absolute risk threshold.

898
00:53:47.186 --> 00:53:50.136
The NNS drops, but you do capture more cases.

899
00:53:50.866 --> 00:53:54.566
Just to contextualize these data, you can see that conventional screening

900
00:53:54.586 --> 00:53:58.116
mammography NNS is 125 to 500,

901
00:53:58.586 --> 00:54:02.536
and then colonoscopy has an NNS for advanced adenomas or cancers of

902
00:54:02.726 --> 00:54:06.466
53. So just to give you some context for guideline-recommended screening forms.

903
00:54:08.726 --> 00:54:12.606
This plot shows risk stratification produced by our model in the validation cohort.

904
00:54:13.086 --> 00:54:16.766
So this top red cumulative incidence curve is the top

905
00:54:16.786 --> 00:54:18.646
percentile of predicted risk per prime.

906
00:54:19.466 --> 00:54:23.166
The navy/black second to bottom

907
00:54:23.406 --> 00:54:27.306
cumulative incidence curve is the 45th to 55th percentile prime

908
00:54:27.366 --> 00:54:29.446
predicted risk, so median risk individuals.

909
00:54:29.466 --> 00:54:33.326
And compared to the median risk individuals, the top predicted risk percentile

910
00:54:33.366 --> 00:54:36.706
has a 7.6 times higher risk of developing PDAC

911
00:54:37.546 --> 00:54:41.392
compared to these median risk individuals.This risk increase is

912
00:54:41.442 --> 00:54:44.962
comparable to individuals with BRCA mutations and ATM

913
00:54:45.002 --> 00:54:48.192
mutations, which are some of the more common PGVs associated with pancreatic

914
00:54:48.202 --> 00:54:52.002
cancer. There are other pathogenic variants in different

915
00:54:52.022 --> 00:54:55.842
genes that are less prevalent and have higher risk increases, but these are

916
00:54:56.542 --> 00:55:00.332
indications currently for NCCN guideline recommended screening.

917
00:55:02.652 --> 00:55:06.442
So we then deployed our model in the UK Biobank just to test,

918
00:55:06.582 --> 00:55:09.902
first of all, how our model would perform in a very different clinical population.

919
00:55:09.942 --> 00:55:12.202
The UK Biobank is largely white British.

920
00:55:12.671 --> 00:55:15.792
It's known to be a healthy cohort. It's not necessarily a healthcare-seeking

921
00:55:15.862 --> 00:55:18.382
population. It's a research population.

922
00:55:18.862 --> 00:55:22.642
And it had a lower incidence of disease than our Optum clinical

923
00:55:23.402 --> 00:55:27.162
cohort. And what you see is that there's a slight over-prediction of

924
00:55:27.202 --> 00:55:30.072
risk with a calibration slope of 0.87 in this

925
00:55:30.222 --> 00:55:33.262
cohort. And the AUC decreases slightly from

926
00:55:33.522 --> 00:55:37.342
0.75 at 36 months to 0.71. But generally

927
00:55:37.422 --> 00:55:41.042
speaking, the generalizability to this very different cohort is

928
00:55:41.282 --> 00:55:42.082
relatively good.

929
00:55:43.462 --> 00:55:46.962
We were also interested to see whether our high-risk individuals in our model were

930
00:55:47.102 --> 00:55:50.672
actually individuals who do not have current guideline recommended

931
00:55:51.022 --> 00:55:54.052
screening indications. And what we see is that the PRIME top one

932
00:55:54.122 --> 00:55:58.062
percentile have PGVs in NCCN-defined

933
00:55:58.162 --> 00:56:01.262
pancreatic cancer risk genes at a prevalence of

934
00:56:01.402 --> 00:56:05.142
1.4%. This is relatively similar to the overall

935
00:56:05.182 --> 00:56:08.302
prevalence of these mutations in the UK Biobank at

936
00:56:08.422 --> 00:56:11.662
1.1%. So we're largely capturing individuals at sporadic

937
00:56:12.082 --> 00:56:14.862
pancreatic cancer risk rather than genetic pancreatic cancer risk.

938
00:56:16.662 --> 00:56:20.062
Our results were relatively consistent across sensitivity analyses,

939
00:56:20.622 --> 00:56:22.462
including analyses meant to

940
00:56:23.382 --> 00:56:27.122
sort of weed out individuals who may already be undergoing a workup for

941
00:56:27.182 --> 00:56:31.102
PDAC, so individuals with PDAC within six months of index

942
00:56:31.142 --> 00:56:33.762
date and individuals with recent abdominal imaging.

943
00:56:35.702 --> 00:56:38.962
So again, I mentioned that we envision this model used in a sort of

944
00:56:39.142 --> 00:56:42.732
sequential case-finding framework, so in which we first

945
00:56:42.742 --> 00:56:46.582
define a high-risk population and then do blood-based biomarker

946
00:56:46.602 --> 00:56:48.462
testing and then ultimately imaging.

947
00:56:48.482 --> 00:56:52.332
So this is just a hypothetical sort of working through this

948
00:56:52.342 --> 00:56:56.212
framework. So if we were to take a population of a million and

949
00:56:56.242 --> 00:56:59.722
take the top 1% highest PRIME predicted risk individuals in this

950
00:56:59.742 --> 00:57:03.662
population and test them with PancreasSure, which is a protein-based pancreatic

951
00:57:03.722 --> 00:57:07.172
cancer assay with a published sensitivity of 80% and

952
00:57:07.722 --> 00:57:11.302
specificity of 90%, we would expect to find 1,054

953
00:57:11.322 --> 00:57:15.082
individuals who were positive, and those individuals would undergo

954
00:57:15.142 --> 00:57:19.042
abdominal imaging. And assuming a sort of optimistic 100% sensitivity

955
00:57:19.062 --> 00:57:22.402
of abdominal imaging for disease, we would identify 62

956
00:57:22.462 --> 00:57:26.382
cases. So this is a positive predictive value of 5.9% with a

957
00:57:26.422 --> 00:57:27.852
likelihood ratio of 47.

958
00:57:29.222 --> 00:57:33.142
If we were to use a different type of blood-based biomarker, so a cell-free

959
00:57:33.222 --> 00:57:36.112
DNA assay, which is known to have a lower sensitivity and a higher

960
00:57:36.202 --> 00:57:40.102
specificity, we would of course have fewer individuals who are eligible

961
00:57:40.142 --> 00:57:41.892
for imaging, 543,

962
00:57:43.122 --> 00:57:46.552
and 47 PDACs identified, so fewer PDACs

963
00:57:46.622 --> 00:57:50.342
identified. But we would have a higher positive predictive value,

964
00:57:50.802 --> 00:57:54.512
demonstrating the trade-off between sensitivity and specificity in these classes of

965
00:57:54.582 --> 00:57:55.542
biomarker assays.

966
00:57:57.562 --> 00:58:01.222
So PRIME is important because it could expand early detection opportunities

967
00:58:01.962 --> 00:58:05.702
for the 80% of patients who currently don't have guideline recommended

968
00:58:06.342 --> 00:58:08.862
screening indications. It's interpretable.

969
00:58:09.262 --> 00:58:12.762
It can be explained to a patient, and it can be implemented easily.

970
00:58:12.842 --> 00:58:16.802
It uses routinely collected EHR data with procedures to handle missing

971
00:58:16.862 --> 00:58:20.822
data, and it's validated across US health systems as well as the

972
00:58:20.882 --> 00:58:24.842
UK Biobank. So in a future perspective validation and

973
00:58:24.942 --> 00:58:28.602
case-finding study, we plan at NYU to flag

974
00:58:28.662 --> 00:58:31.962
individuals with PRIME predicted absolute two-year risk of greater than

975
00:58:32.022 --> 00:58:32.902
0.5%,

976
00:58:33.802 --> 00:58:36.982
then test those individuals with blood-based biomarker tests, likely a

977
00:58:37.002 --> 00:58:40.802
protein-based assay, and among individuals positive at

978
00:58:40.862 --> 00:58:44.662
both first two steps of the sequence, we will then apply diagnostic imaging.

979
00:58:46.602 --> 00:58:49.982
So I want to give acknowledgement to my co-authors, including my mentor, Dr.

980
00:58:50.202 --> 00:58:53.901
Morgan Grams, at the NYU Division of Precision Medicine, my

981
00:58:53.962 --> 00:58:56.302
colleagues at the Perlmutter Cancer Center, including Drs.

982
00:58:56.342 --> 00:59:00.222
Ganda and Maitra, who were important in this study, as well as my colleagues

983
00:59:00.302 --> 00:59:03.511
in population health. Feel free to contact me if you have any

984
00:59:03.542 --> 00:59:07.382
questions. And I think we have a little bit of time for questions now as

985
00:59:07.422 --> 00:59:11.362
well, and the full manuscript is available now in JAMA Oncology

986
00:59:11.382 --> 00:59:15.141
via the QR code below if you want to know more details. Thank you.

987
00:59:16.212 --> 00:59:24.902
I'll

988
00:59:27.562 --> 00:59:31.502
ask a question about the methods. Great talk.

989
00:59:32.462 --> 00:59:36.182
When you designed your models to do the prediction,

990
00:59:36.302 --> 00:59:40.162
did you build in sort of balance between the two groups, the

991
00:59:40.202 --> 00:59:42.342
PDAC group versus the not PDAC group?

992
00:59:42.402 --> 00:59:46.322
Or you were able to predict even though it was a rare outcome?

993
00:59:46.562 --> 00:59:49.102
Yeah. We didn't use any sort of class weighting.

994
00:59:49.842 --> 00:59:51.662
We did not build in any balance.

995
00:59:52.002 --> 00:59:55.542
Okay. And any thoughts about the prevalence of those

996
00:59:55.582 --> 00:59:59.222
conditions and how those might fluctuate in different populations and

997
00:59:59.242 --> 01:00:02.682
therefore impact the sensitivity and specificity?

998
01:00:03.422 --> 01:00:03.722
So

999
01:00:04.682 --> 01:00:06.542
the prevalence of the risk factors in the model?

1000
01:00:06.572 --> 01:00:07.122
Yeah, the risk factors.

1001
01:00:07.662 --> 01:00:10.402
Yeah. They certainly will vary across populations.

1002
01:00:10.442 --> 01:00:13.932
Like for example, in the UK Biobank, the prevalence of type 2 diabetes is much

1003
01:00:13.962 --> 01:00:17.862
lower than the Optum population. We

1004
01:00:17.942 --> 01:00:21.842
hope that if we're capturing real biological signal, that our absolute

1005
01:00:21.882 --> 01:00:25.282
risk predictions will be sort of calibrated across different prevalences of these

1006
01:00:25.402 --> 01:00:26.762
risk factors. But,

1007
01:00:27.582 --> 01:00:28.262
I think that's why

1008
01:00:29.402 --> 01:00:32.042
prospective validation of this sort of model will be important to

1009
01:00:32.962 --> 01:00:35.462
show that it's actually predicting risk correctly.

1010
01:00:36.242 --> 01:00:36.682
Thank you.

1011
01:00:39.082 --> 01:00:40.542
Yeah. Just great talk.

1012
01:00:41.522 --> 01:00:45.442
I was looking at your hypothetical model, which I really liked how you kind

1013
01:00:45.482 --> 01:00:49.306
of presented it, and you were thinking about-The second

1014
01:00:49.406 --> 01:00:53.376
step, looking at the imaging. Now, how are you thinking about using

1015
01:00:53.426 --> 01:00:57.406
that data? Because you've kind of alluded to the possibility

1016
01:00:57.466 --> 01:01:01.326
of detecting 62 cancers, but now with a lot

1017
01:01:01.366 --> 01:01:05.246
of improvements in using radiomics, AI

1018
01:01:05.326 --> 01:01:06.886
methods,

1019
01:01:08.406 --> 01:01:09.116
