My name is Houyi Zhang, and I'm an earth stem and tenure-track investigator

1591
01:34:04.590 --> 01:34:08.310
at National Cancer Institute. So it's my great pleasure

1592
01:34:08.370 --> 01:34:12.010
to present the CONFLUENCE Project, which is an unprecedented

1593
01:34:12.130 --> 01:34:12.570
effort

1594
01:34:13.870 --> 01:34:15.710
for breast cancer genome-wide association study.

1595
01:34:16.350 --> 01:34:20.130
We have been able to pull more than two million participants from diverse

1596
01:34:20.150 --> 01:34:23.790
ancestries. And at this scale, we are able to uncover some of the genetic

1597
01:34:23.890 --> 01:34:26.650
insights which are not even possible before.

1598
01:34:28.710 --> 01:34:30.990
I have no financial relationship to disclosure.

1599
01:34:32.410 --> 01:34:36.290
So genome-wide association study for breast cancer has been successful

1600
01:34:36.350 --> 01:34:40.190
so far. Up to today, there are around 240 risk

1601
01:34:40.270 --> 01:34:44.150
loci being identified and explaining around 30%

1602
01:34:44.210 --> 01:34:45.790
of the familial risk for breast cancer.

1603
01:34:46.450 --> 01:34:49.890
However, the GWAS data for breast cancer are

1604
01:34:50.230 --> 01:34:54.090
mainly from European ancestry, and the corresponding polygenic risk score developed

1605
01:34:54.190 --> 01:34:57.810
based on this data showed reduced performance in non-European

1606
01:34:57.830 --> 01:35:01.610
ancestry. Now, this disparity actually matters a lot because breast

1607
01:35:01.650 --> 01:35:04.730
cancer is the most common cancer in women worldwide.

1608
01:35:05.690 --> 01:35:09.539
Roughly per year, there are more than two million women diagnosed,

1609
01:35:09.850 --> 01:35:12.550
and the lifetime risk for women is roughly one in eight.

1610
01:35:13.890 --> 01:35:15.530
So to address this gap,

1611
01:35:16.550 --> 01:35:20.350
we have built this CONFLUENCE project, which is the largest

1612
01:35:20.590 --> 01:35:23.610
and most ancestrally diverse project for breast cancer GWAS.

1613
01:35:24.330 --> 01:35:28.250
CONFLUENCE is actually a consortium of consortium, where there are six major

1614
01:35:28.270 --> 01:35:32.060
participating consortium of CONFLUENCE from different ancestries, and there are

1615
01:35:32.130 --> 01:35:35.870
also multiple biobanks, which are contributing data to CONFLUENCE.

1616
01:35:36.550 --> 01:35:40.510
Up to today, there are around 290 studies from 61 different

1617
01:35:40.590 --> 01:35:44.550
countries in CONFLUENCE. And the goal of CONFLUENCE is simple and

1618
01:35:44.570 --> 01:35:48.190
also very ambitious, including identifying novel risk loci

1619
01:35:48.230 --> 01:35:49.570
associated with breast cancer risk,

1620
01:35:50.550 --> 01:35:53.770
develop a polygenic risk score that is truly generalizable across different

1621
01:35:53.790 --> 01:35:57.410
ancestries, identify potential loci which are associated with

1622
01:35:57.490 --> 01:35:59.230
prognosis and long-term survival.

1623
01:35:59.810 --> 01:36:03.430
Last and the most important is trying to build a reusable data sources

1624
01:36:03.770 --> 01:36:05.650
that is open to the whole scientific community.

1625
01:36:07.770 --> 01:36:11.610
So CONFLUENCE is the largest breast cancer GWAS that has been ever

1626
01:36:11.630 --> 01:36:15.230
conducted. Compared to the most recent multi-ancestry GWAS

1627
01:36:15.290 --> 01:36:18.550
effort for breast cancer, based on the effective sample size,

1628
01:36:18.890 --> 01:36:22.750
CONFLUENCE contributed more than three times larger sample size, and we have been

1629
01:36:22.830 --> 01:36:25.770
able to analyze data that has roughly

1630
01:36:26.030 --> 01:36:29.590
227,000 cases and around

1631
01:36:29.710 --> 01:36:30.930
1.7 million controls.

1632
01:36:32.460 --> 01:36:36.350
And CONFLUENCE is not only about increasing the sample size, we have also

1633
01:36:36.390 --> 01:36:40.130
put a decent effort of trying to increase the sample size for all non-European

1634
01:36:40.170 --> 01:36:44.150
ancestries. In this figure, it shows the effective sample size for

1635
01:36:44.230 --> 01:36:45.930
five major ancestries in CONFLUENCE.

1636
01:36:46.390 --> 01:36:50.120
From the left to right, it includes African and mixed

1637
01:36:50.190 --> 01:36:53.330
American, East Asian, Middle Eastern, and South Asian.

1638
01:36:53.970 --> 01:36:57.670
And we have been able to double the effective sample size for every single

1639
01:36:57.690 --> 01:36:59.060
non-European ancestry in CONFLUENCE.

1640
01:37:00.990 --> 01:37:03.870
So as you can imagine, there are so many different studies and arrays

1641
01:37:03.880 --> 01:37:07.430
contributing to CONFLUENCE. So the quality control

1642
01:37:07.530 --> 01:37:09.730
process takes a humongous effort.

1643
01:37:10.130 --> 01:37:13.810
And we have paid a lot of efforts trying to harmonize the genotype quality

1644
01:37:13.910 --> 01:37:17.470
process to ensure all the data are processed in a consistent way.

1645
01:37:18.150 --> 01:37:22.070
And all the data are imputed to top matching panel, and in total, there are

1646
01:37:22.110 --> 01:37:25.190
around 45 million variants analyzed within CONFLUENCE.

1647
01:37:25.710 --> 01:37:29.450
Association study have been done based on Regeni, adjusting for top 10

1648
01:37:29.470 --> 01:37:33.430
principal components. And additionally, GWAS summary statistics

1649
01:37:33.490 --> 01:37:36.630
from 20 different external biobanks has been included in this

1650
01:37:36.710 --> 01:37:40.374
effort.So, this is a

1651
01:37:40.414 --> 01:37:43.714
Manhattan plot of the Confluence meta-analysis.

1652
01:37:43.974 --> 01:37:47.774
This is combining all ancestries together, overall breast cancer studies, and

1653
01:37:47.914 --> 01:37:51.894
we have been able to identify 545 independent loci.

1654
01:37:52.214 --> 01:37:55.874
And this number defined is based on three very stringent criteria,

1655
01:37:56.374 --> 01:38:00.154
including all the index variant for each loci need to be 500

1656
01:38:00.274 --> 01:38:04.154
KB away from each other, and their LD need to be less than

1657
01:38:04.174 --> 01:38:06.414
0.1, and D-prime need to be less than 0.3.

1658
01:38:06.784 --> 01:38:10.594
And you need to fulfill all the three criteria simultaneously to be defined as

1659
01:38:10.654 --> 01:38:11.814
one independent loci.

1660
01:38:12.634 --> 01:38:15.214
And we also ensure every single contributing study

1661
01:38:16.274 --> 01:38:18.374
have very well type 1 error control.

1662
01:38:18.754 --> 01:38:21.974
As you can see, the total genomic inflation factor is only

1663
01:38:22.274 --> 01:38:26.234
1.11 for this kind of large-scale study, indicating a very

1664
01:38:26.254 --> 01:38:30.114
well-controlled type 1 error. The minimum allele frequency we have been able to

1665
01:38:30.194 --> 01:38:34.034
go to is 0.03%, and the number of genomewide significant variants

1666
01:38:34.454 --> 01:38:36.134
is more than 63,000.

1667
01:38:38.174 --> 01:38:41.954
And after removing all the previously published loci by

1668
01:38:42.014 --> 01:38:45.914
any literature, following very similar stringent criteria to define

1669
01:38:45.954 --> 01:38:49.294
at least one novel loci, we have been able to identify more than

1670
01:38:49.974 --> 01:38:53.554
273 novel loci which haven't been published by any previous

1671
01:38:53.614 --> 01:38:54.154
literature.

1672
01:38:56.394 --> 01:38:59.914
And based on the GWAS, we have also conducted a preliminary

1673
01:39:00.454 --> 01:39:03.814
PRS analysis. This PRS is the simplest PRS.

1674
01:39:04.094 --> 01:39:07.314
It is constructed directly based on the genomewide significant variants.

1675
01:39:07.474 --> 01:39:11.354
The index loci will take out two major biobanks from the analysis,

1676
01:39:11.634 --> 01:39:15.514
UK Biobank and All of Us. And the PRS building process is

1677
01:39:15.554 --> 01:39:19.274
completely independent from these two biobank to ensure the independence of PRS

1678
01:39:19.314 --> 01:39:19.834
construction.

1679
01:39:20.674 --> 01:39:24.554
The variant entering this PRS is 544 because one of the loci is

1680
01:39:24.594 --> 01:39:28.334
only UK Biobank available. We compared against a widely

1681
01:39:28.414 --> 01:39:32.254
used 313-variant breast cancer PRS, which has been actually implemented

1682
01:39:32.374 --> 01:39:36.334
in some of the clinical trials to test PRS efficiency in

1683
01:39:36.354 --> 01:39:39.954
breast cancer prevention. And we also acknowledge there are

1684
01:39:40.114 --> 01:39:44.094
many advanced PRS approaches that can actually accounting for LD

1685
01:39:46.294 --> 01:39:49.474
effect size and the minor allele frequency differences across ancestries.

1686
01:39:49.504 --> 01:39:52.714
And there has been effort in multiple different ancestries to

1687
01:39:53.574 --> 01:39:55.774
